 listed along with its original form <i>Brousse</i> in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors."],"variants":[{"name":"Brousse","meanings":["(2010: NA)","French: topographic name for someone living in a scrubby area, from Old French <i>bro(u)ce</i> ‘thicket, brushwood’ (from Late Latin <i>bruscia</i>), or a habitational name from any of several places in France named Brousse. Compare   Bruce   and   Brusse  .","History: This surname is listed in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors (along with its altered form <i>Bruce</i>) and also in the similar register of the Huguenot Society of South Carolina."]},{"name":"Brewis","meanings":["English:","(of Norman origin): habitational name from Briouze in Orne.","(Northumberland and Durham): topographic name or nickname from Middle English <i>breuhous</i> ‘brewery’ (literally ‘brew house’)."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomas Bruce 1st Baron of Clackmannan was born in 1328, in Clackmannan, Clackmannanshire, Scotland, United Kingdom, his father, Sir Thomas Bruce of Annandale, was 44 and his mother, Helen Erskine, was 42. He married Marjorie Charteris of Stenhouse about 1340, in Clackmannan, Clackmannanshire, Scotland. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1348, in Scotland, United Kingdom, at the age of 20, and was buried in Clackmannan Churchyard, Clackmannan, Clackmannanshire, Scotland, United Kingdom."},"et":{"132